metadata.title: Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil
aws::graph::propositions: Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil Aircraft Features and Configurations
Later-production Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil aircraft feature new avionics.
Later-production Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil aircraft integrate an Automatic Flight Control System (AFCS).
Later-production Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil aircraft integrate an autopilot.
Later-production Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil aircraft feature a glass cockpit.
The glass cockpit features three liquid-crystal displays (LCDs).
Later-production Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil aircraft feature digital avionics.
Digital avionics include the synthetic-vision terrain mapping system.
Digital avionics include Airbus's Multibloc center console.
Radios may be mounted on the Multibloc center console.
The Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil has proven popular in a range of roles.
Multiple cabin configurations can be used in the Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil.
The Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil typically seats between four and six passengers.
Large sliding doors can be fitted to either side of the Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil cabin.
Some operators design cabin furnishings to enable rapid reconfiguration of internal space.
Some operators design cabin furnishings to enable rapid reconfiguration of equipment fit-out.
Rapid reconfiguration allows aircraft to be switched between roles.
Public service operators often have forward looking infrared (FLIR) cameras installed on their Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil aircraft.
Law enforcement operators are considered public service operators.
Public service operators often have mission systems installed on their Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil aircraft.

text:
Later-production aircraft feature new avionics and systems such as the integration of an Automatic Flight Control System (AFCS) and autopilot, a glass cockpit featuring three liquid-crystal displays (LCDs) and digital avionics, such as the synthetic-vision terrain mapping system and Airbus's Multibloc center console upon which radios may be mounted.
The AS350 has proven popular in a range of roles; multiple cabin configurations can be used, between four and six passengers in a typical seating configuration, and large sliding doors can be fitted to either side of the cabin. In some operators' fleets, the furnishings of the cabin has been designed to enable the internal space and/or equipment fit-out to be rapidly reconfigured to enable aircraft to be switched between roles.

Public service operators, such as those in law enforcement, often have forward looking infrared (FLIR) cameras and other mission systems installed on their aircraft.
